cs.IT, cs.SI, cs.SD, cs.SOC, cs.AI 

The paper discusses the use of information-theoretic quantities for the empirical study of decision-making and information flows in social systems. This suggests that the paper could belong to several arXiv CS sub-categories, including cs.IT (Information Theory), cs.SI (Social and Information Networks), cs.SD (Software Engineering), cs.SOC (Social and Information Networks), and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). However, given the focus on information theory and its axiomatic relationships, cs.IT is the most likely sub-category. The use of empirical methods and statistical bootstrapping also suggests a possible fit with cs.SI and cs.SOC. The examples provided of the British Criminal Court system and the Afghanistan insurgency suggest a possible fit with cs.SD and cs.AI, respectively.
